Generates a pseudo-random 256-bit salt.
The salt can be included in an 0x order, ensuring that the order generates a unique orderHash
and will not collide with other outstanding orders that are identical in all other parameters.

comment.shortText:
A baseUnit is defined as the smallest denomination of a token. An amount expressed in baseUnits
is the amount expressed in the smallest denomination.
E.g: 1 unit of a token with 18 decimal places is expressed in baseUnits as 1000000000000000000

comment.text: The amount of units that you would like converted to baseUnits.
The number of decimal places the unit amount has.

comment.shortText:
A unit amount is defined as the amount of a token above the specified decimal places (integer part).
E.g: If a currency has 18 decimal places, 1e18 or one quintillion of the currency is equivalent
to 1 unit.

comment.text: The amount in baseUnits that you would like converted to units.
The number of decimal places the unit amount has.

comment.shortText:
Fills a signed order with an amount denominated in baseUnits of the taker token.
Since the order in which transactions are included in the next block is indeterminate, race-conditions
could arise where a users balance or allowance changes before the fillOrder executes. Because of this,
we allow you to specify `shouldCheckTransfer`. If true, the smart contract will not throw if while
executing, the parties do not have sufficient balances/allowances, preserving gas costs. Setting it to
false forgoes this check and causes the smart contract to throw (using all the gas supplied) instead.

comment.text: A JS object that conforms to the SignedOrder interface.
The amount of the order (in taker tokens baseUnits) that you wish to fill.

Whether or not you wish for the contract call to throw if upon
                                 execution the tokens cannot be transferred.

The user Ethereum address who would like to fill this order.
                                 Must be available via the supplied Web3.Provider passed to 0x.js.

comment.shortText:
Sequentially and atomically fills signedOrders up to the specified takerTokenFillAmount.
If the fill amount is reached - it succeeds and does not fill the rest of the orders.
If fill amount is not reached - it fills as much of the fill amount as possible and succeeds.

                                 some cannot be filled.

The user Ethereum address who would like to fill these orders.

comment.shortText: Elliptic Curve signature
Source: https://stackoverflow.com/a/29837695/3546986

Converts BigNumber instance to BN
The only reason we convert to BN is to remain compatible with `ethABI. soliditySHA3` that
expects values of Solidity type `uint` to be passed as type `BN`.
We do not use BN anywhere else in the codebase.
